“People do not decide to become extraordinary. They decide to accomplish extraordinary things.”

Sir Tim Berners-Lee, a British computer scientist who is globally notorious for his masterpiece, the “World Wide Web”. Born on June 8,1955 ,TimBL was naturally captivated towards computing because of his parents who worked on the Ferranti Mark I, the first commercial computer.

Right from his childhood days the art of learning served as his charisma. From working as an independent contractor at CERN to building his very own prototype system “ENQUIRE”, Sir Tim Berners-Lee has always been the epitome of “Master at Work”. In 2004 he was awarded a Knighthood by Queen Elizabeth II and still gracing the mankind as a Professional Fellow at University of Oxford and as a Professor at Massachusetts Institute of Technology.

So we here at ISTE NIT DURGAPUR CHAPTER, celebrating the day of this legend,are wholeheartedly obliged for his every contribution.

#iste #birthday #timbernerslee

node.text:
“Every parting is a form of death, as every reunion is a type of heaven.”

Struck by a surge of heart-rending emotions,we are feeling a relentless amount of grief and sorrow to part with those who had become our family, a part of our lives. For now, bringing our emotional outburst to a standstill, we all would like to wholeheartedly express our heartiest love and gratitude to our seniors who had  been our true friend, philosopher and guide ,always leading and inspiring us on facing new challenges in life and emerge victorious, vanquishing them.As time demands it, camouflaging our emotions as much as possible, we all juniors of ISTE NIT Durgapur, would like to bid farewell to our senior batch of 2021 with all our respect and gratitude. Thanks to all of you for making our memorabilia rich and glorious and adding value to our lives.Wishing you all an astounding and remarkable future in the years to come. 

Adieu Messieurs and Mesdames!

#farewell #iste #batchof2021

Eid-al-Fitr, also called the “Festival of Breaking the Fast", is a religious festival celebrated by Muslims worldwide that marks the end of the month-long dawn-to-sunset fasting of Ramadan.  Muslims wait to see the new moon so that they can start the festivities on the next morning.  This pious day is celebrated to Express gratitude to the almighty Allah for all that we have. It is said that when Mohammad arrived in Medina, he found people celebrating on two specific days. Mohammad said that Allah had fixed these days- Eid-al-Fitr and Eid-al-Fitr. That’s how Eid-al-Fitr originated.  It is believed that Prophet Mohammad got the first vision of the holy Quran during the month of Ramadan. Sunni Muslims praise Allah in a loud voice and chant their prayers whereas according to Shia procedure, prayers start with the Niyat followed by five Takbirs. On this day, Muslims decorate their homes, help poor people, have delicacies and perform social gatherings. 
 
On this auspicious day, ISTE NIT Durgapur wishes everyone a happy Eid-al-Fitr and wish that may Allah bless us with good health amid this pandemic.

“It's not that we use technology, we live technology” - Godfrey Reggio.

Every year May 11 is observed as the National Technology Day. A golden feather ornamenting the Indian Technological achievements, this day marks the anniversary of the Pokhran Nuclear Test of 1998. Since then, every year this day is dedicated as an homage to all the Engineers and Scientists, who not only work day in and day out, but dedicate a major part of their life for the betterment of the humanity. From the depths of the Mariana trench to the periphery of the space, technology is omnipresent, lighting every darkness. The significance of this year’s  theme,'Science and Technology for a sustainable future', is well known and remind us of the need to upgrade ourselves.

So, we here at ISTE NIT DURGAPUR CHAPTER, wishes all the techno enthusiasts out there, a very optimistic National Technology Day. Let’s together “Learn, Invent and Evolve”.

“The highest education is that which does not merely give us information but makes our life in harmony with all existence.” ~Rabindranath Tagore
 
9th May every year marks the birth anniversary of the Bard of Bengal, Rabindranath Tagore. Born and brought up in an affluent Bengali family, Tagore was a great Bengali poet, novelist, scholar, playwright, humanist and philosopher. His works are a perfect blend of pious theology and Indian poetry, most of them reflecting politics, personal issues and oppression of women. The first Asian to win a Nobel Prize, Tagore's “Jana Gana Mana" has been adopted as the national anthem of India. He is also the writer of the national anthem of Bangladesh. He was a constant motivator during the time of Indian Independence and seeing the plight of Indians in the Jallianwala Bagh Tragedy, he renounced the title “Knight.” "Where the clear stream of reason has not lost its way" shows how he motivated people to achieve an ideal society.
 
As we celebrate literature and music on this day, ISTE NIT Durgapur wishes everyone an auspicious Rabindra Jayanti on the birthday of Kobiguru.
 

Credits to @allusubbu for the magnificent sketch

“Without labour nothing prospers.” – Sophocles.

A day dedicated to the all the workers across this planet, a day marking its origin in the labour union movement in the United States in the 19th Century, a day that is nothing less than a festival celebrated globally. Every year May 1 is celebrated as the International Labour Day to a pay a tribute to every worker out there putting in his blood and sweat, irrespective of the field, for the betterment of society, making us believe that may be not alone but together, greatness can be achieved.

So today we here at ISTE NIT DURGAPUR CHAPTER greets everyone a very enthusiastic International Labour Day with an impulse to cherish every work and profession, every worker in any profession deserves equal esteem.

#labourday #mayday

It has always been a great pride and honour for all of us to carry forward the legacy of our prestigious club, the Indian Society for Technical Education(ISTE) NIT Durgapur Students Chapter. Since its birth in 1995, ISTE being rooted in the heart and soul of NIT Durgapur has been the torchbearer to many successful endeavours for our student community at large. Just like every year, this year too, passing the glorious legacy down onto new responsible shoulders, we here at ISTE NIT Durgapur, with all the pride, honour and glory, would like to wholeheartedly congratulate each and every new member of the ISTE board from the inner depths of our heart. Let us make this moment memorable by inscribing it in the golden pages of our memorabilia as we all look forward to our new post holders who would surely take the glory of ISTE to all new heights filling its archive with great achievements, success and undertakings in the future days to come.

"IT IS BETTER TO WIN OVER SELF THAN TO WIN OVER A MILLION ENEMIES" -
Vardhamana Mahavira

Mahavir Jayanti or Mahavir Janma Kalyanak is one of the most prominent festivals of the country celebrated with utmost zeal. The festival marks the birth anniversary of Lord Mahavira, also known as Vardhamana. Lord Mahavir is considered as the founder of Jainism and the twenty-fourth and last Tirthankara of Jainism.He devoted his entire life preaching the truth about spiritual freedom to the world. He taught his followers about the importance of non-violence and introduced the concept of salvation.Mahavir Jayanti is not only limited in India but across the globe Jain community celebrates it. On this day, members of Jain community offer prayers, read religious rhymes and seek the blessings of the deity for a healthy and prosperous life.

On this propitious occasion, We at ISTE NIT Durgapur, wish you all a very happy and auspicious Mahavir Jayanti. May Lord Mahavir fulfill all your dreams and bless you all with knowledge and joy.

#festivevibes #stayblessed #MahavirJayanti

"What is the use of a fine house if you haven't got a tolerable planet to put it on?" ~ Henry David Thoreau

April 22 is commended as the World Earth Day to exhibit support for the well being of the Earth and raise open mindfulness about the issue. World Earth Day is praised worldwide to make mindfulness about the consistently expanding global warming, pollution and deforestation and to advise openly about the cataclysmic influences it has on our day to day lives. On this day, a few volunteers go to a close-by land to plant trees for a greener planet while a few volunteers choose to clean neighbouring paths or waterways. Various specialists hold hands and attempt to make open mindfulness by making banners, through origami ventures or their works of art. This year, the theme is RESTORE OUR EARTH, which focuses on organic processes and innovative thinking to restore our ecosystems and save Mother Earth.

ISTE NIT Durgapur wishes a Happy Earth Day to all and asks everybody to stay at home. Let’s keep the hope alive that this too shall pass.

Ram Navami, a sacred day for the Hindus, a day that the marks the birth of the most ideal man that ever walked this earth, Lord Rama, the seventh incarnation of Lord Vishnu. The festival falls on the ninth day of Shukla Paksha in the Hindu calendar in the month of Chaitra. Lord Rama throughout his lifetime on this mortal earth was a man of dignity. Earning the name of “Maryada Purushottam”, the entire life of Lord Rama gives us a message that one thing that can never betray you is your morals. 

So we here at ISTE NIT DURGAPUR CHAPTER wishes everyone a very happy Ram Navami with a belief that no matter how devastating the evil is, the good shall always thrive in us.

#RamNavami
